    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA174-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi vantu eytiya kālattu āṟṟāḷāya talaiviyait tōḻi vaṟpuṟīi niṉṟāṭku avaḷ colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what she said to the confidante who kept encouraging HER who was unable to bear it at a time when [HE] had come back after finishing [his] work.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA174">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kaṟṟai yīntiṉ muṟṟukkulai yaṉṉa</l>
<l>            vāḷi lattat tāḷam pōntaik</l>
<l>            kōḷuṭai neṭuñciṉai yāṇkural viḷippiṟ</l>
<l>            puliyetir vaḻaṅkum vaḷivaḻaṅ kāriṭaic</l>
<l>            ceṉṟa kātalar vantiṉitu muyaṅkip </l>
<l>            piriyā toruvaḻi yuṟaiyiṉum peritaḻin</l>
<l>            tuyaṅkiṉai maṭantai yeṉṟi tōḻi</l>
<l>            yaṟṟu mākumaḵ taṟiyā tōrkkē</l>
<l>            vīḻāk koḷkai vīḻnta koṇṭi</l>
<l rend="indent4">            pularpukaḻ mūtūrp paṉittuṟai yaṉṉa</l>
<l>            mallaṉ mārpu maṭuttaṉaṉ </l>
<l>            pullumaṟ ṟevaṉō vaṉpilaṅ kaṭaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“Although [your] lover, who had gone</l>
<l rend="indent">the wind-blown difficult way where the tiger faces [anyone]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">etir vaḻaṅkum</term>: "to wander against" = "to face"? T.V.G. gives here a scholastic interpretation of the tiger roaring out against the sound made by the male bird.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">to the sound of the male [bird] on the clustered long branch</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the [long-]trunked palmyra tree on a road devoid of men,</l>
<l rend="indent3">resembling the ripening bunches on the bundled date palm,</l>
<l rend="indent4">has come [and] embraced [you] sweetly,</l>
<l rend="indent">[although] he doesn't separate and stays the same way,</l>
<l>you are greatly desolate [and] become weak, girl”,</l>
<l rend="indent4">you said, friend.</l>
<l>And thus it is to those who don't know that.</l>
<l>He united [his] broad chest,</l>
<l rend="indent3">{as the chilly ghat in an old village [full of] praise when it dawns,}</l>
<l rend="indent2">with a harlot, lowering [his] unyielding<note place="foot">There is a play with <term xml:lang="ta">vīḻā - vīḻnta</term> here. T.V.G. explains it to mean desire here, but I feel that the idea of principles coming down is more natural.</note> principles.</l>
<l>What of but embracing, when there is no love with us?<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṉp’ ilam-kaṭai</term>: cf. the identical expression in KT 93.4. I am nowadays inclined to explain this as a locative formation (which is not inconceivable with il, which does not distinguish at all between participial and finite forms). And then we would have to take it either as a convolute construction (<term xml:lang="ta">nam-kaṭai aṉp’ il</term>) or as locative for a dative: "what is this to us who are without love?"</note></l>
        </lg>
         </div>
